                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/1025: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-06-05T13:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 5, 1930—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>182. Your 374, May 27, 6 p.m. You are authorized in your discretion and on
                    specific request of American interest concerned to protest to <hi rend="italic"
                        >de facto</hi> Northern authorities if and when such authorities impose
                    taxes on American petroleum or other products when accompanied by transit passes
                    issued by the recognized and appropriate Chinese authorities purporting to
                    exempt the products in question from all taxation in transit.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
